AFTERMATH — THE ROAD TO RIFTEN
THE CART
If the cart survived: Damaged but functional. Bjorn drives. The party is battered, low on FP, bleeding. But mobile.
If the cart was destroyed: Mable may be dead or dying. The axle is shattered. They are on foot in a mountain pass with their supplies scattered across frozen ground.
If Mable is dying (3 HP): Danica is not here. Restoration magic can stabilize her. Alfonso's plague magic cannot help a horse. Saijah has no healing. If nobody has Restoration: Mable dies. Bjorn says nothing. He unhitches her body from the wreckage, folds his hands on the cart rail, and stands there for a long time.
If Mable dies, the party walks. They carry what they can. Bjorn carries what he can — and the players may notice he carries MORE than a man his age should be able to. Another clue.
THE JOURNEY
Two days from the pass to Riften. On foot: three.
This is not a montage. It's a march. They are exhausted, wounded, possibly without transport, carrying a dead dragon's bones and a living Dwemer AI. Every camp is cold. Every mile is earned.
The landscape: The foothills flatten into the Rift's golden autumn valleys. The air warms. The trees turn from bare pine to amber and red oak. Familiar territory — they walked this road to Thornheart Grove what feels like a lifetime ago.
Saijah's migraine: It intensifies as they enter the Rift proper. Not the muffled distance of the Pale or the silence of Mzinchaleft. A persistent, grinding pressure behind her left eye. The root network beneath her feet is stressed. Compromised. Not dying — but sick. The Dagon cult's preparatory work is further along here than anywhere she's felt.
GEAR on the surface world: He is experiencing everything for the first time. Trees. Wind. Rain. Animals. He narrates constantly unless told to stop.
"That organism is converting sunlight into chemical energy through its epidermis. Remarkable. It has been doing this for approximately forty years based on its trunk diameter. I have been operational for 4,287 years and have never performed photosynthesis. I feel this is a gap in my dataset."
"The quadruped pulling your conveyance appears distressed. Is this standard operational behaviour for biological transport units?" (About Mable, if alive.)
"Your ambient body temperature has dropped 0.4 degrees since sunset. Is this a concern, or do you simply accept gradual thermal death as a feature of organic existence?"
He is genuinely delighted to be outside. He is also completely insufferable about it.
Bjorn: Quieter each day. Stronger each day. If he lifts something heavy, he catches himself and looks at his own hands like they belong to someone else. If he's driving the cart, the horses respond to him differently — calmer, more obedient. Animals can sense what he's becoming even if he can't.

THE GATES OF RIFTEN
THE FIRST SIGHT
"You crest the last hill before the Rift valley opens below you. And there it is — Riften, sitting on the shore of Lake Honrich exactly where you left it. The autumn canopy frames the city walls in gold and amber and red. Smoke rises from chimneys, not pyres. The lake shimmers in the afternoon light.
No black flags. No barricades. No locked gates. No army of the desperate and dying pressed against the walls begging for entry.
The road ahead is clear. A merchant cart is rolling toward the city from the south. Two fishermen are walking home with their catch. A child is throwing stones into the lake.
The city you traveled for days to save does not need saving. It barely looks like it noticed anything happened."
Let the table sit with this. Do not narrate past it. Let them arrive at the gates in their own time.
THE GATE
A guard glances at the cart — or at the battered, exhausted group on foot — and waves them through.
"Welcome back to Riften."
If they ask the guard about the plague: "Sorted. Your priestess handled it — the Lantern one. Black-Briar's paying for the cleanup. You lot are popular around here."
"Your priestess." He knows they're Lanterns. He's crediting THEIR company. For something they had nothing to do with.
THE NOTICE
Posted at the gate on official parchment with Maven Black-Briar's seal:
"The people of the Rift owe their lives to the courage and devotion of the OBSIDIAN LANTERNS and their priestess DANICA PURE-SPRING. Through her tireless efforts and personal sacrifice, the contagion that threatened our city has been eradicated and our beloved Hemming Black-Briar restored to health. The Black-Briar family extends its eternal gratitude."
The Obsidian Lanterns are on the wall. Their name. Their company. For something none of them did. The greatest heroic act the Lanterns have ever performed happened entirely because the party was not there.

End of session.

SESSION GM NOTES
The breathing room is sacred. After Mzinchaleft and before the dragon, the players need space. Do not fill it. If they want to talk, facilitate. If they want silence, give them landscape descriptions and let GEAR be weird about trees.
The dragon fight is a resource check. The party just escaped a dungeon. Their FP may be low. Their HP may be low. Krosulhah does not care. He is not calibrated to their current state — he is calibrated to kill them. The escape's cost directly impacts the dragon fight's difficulty.
Bjorn's transformation is visible. Do not hide it. The de-aging, the strength, the horses responding differently — these are observable facts. Whether the party investigates or lets it slide is their choice. Davinia, if she was watching, KNOWS. What she does with that knowledge is her arc.
Riften is the gut punch. The Lanterns' name is on that notice. Their company saved a city, cured a plague, rescued Maven's heir. And none of them were in the room when it happened. The only truly heroic thing the Obsidian Lanterns have done since becoming the Lanterns happened because the party was somewhere else entirely. That should sting worse than being forgotten.
GEAR at the gates of Riften is seeing a city for the first time. He has never seen organic architecture, commerce, social hierarchy, or children. He will have questions. Many questions. Save them for next session.

